  "text": "Several lines of evidence are compatible with the view that LFY movement is non-targeted. First, GFP-LFY fusions produced in the L1 formed limited gradients extending into deeper layers. Their movement range was between that of 2×GFP and NLS:2×GFP, which move in a non-targeted fashion [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . This is in contrast to the nearly uniform distribution in the shoot apex (reflecting an active mechanism of cell-to-cell transport) that is observed when a viral movement protein fusion is expressed in the L1. Second, size affects LFY movement, as native LFY was more effective in rescuing lfy defects in adjacent cells in the same tissue layer than the larger GLFY fusion. The effect of size is one of the prominent characteristics of non-targeted movement . Third, although differing in stability and sub-cellular localization, all three GFP-LFY truncations and fusions of four mutant lfy alleles were able to X. Wu and others move from the L1 into interior cell layers. Although one cannot exclude the possibility that LFY has several redundant movement signals, the simpler explanation is that the LFY protein sequence does not contain a specific movement or export signal.",
